# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anise
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anise/4-anisaldehyde] Anisaldehyde is prepared commercially by oxidation of 4-methoxytoluene (*p*-cresyl methyl ether) using manganese dioxide to convert a methyl group to the aldehyde group.
[src:anise/4-anisaldehyde] It can also be produced by oxidation of anethole, a related fragrance that is found in some alcoholic beverages, by oxidative cleavage of an alkene.
[src:anise/4-anisaldehyde] Being structurally related to vanillin, 4-anisaldehyde is widely used in the fragrance and flavour industry.
[src:anise/4-anisaldehyde] It is used as an intermediate in the synthesis of other compounds important in pharmaceuticals and perfumery.
[src:anise/4-anisaldehyde] The related *ortho* isomer has a scent of liquorice.
[src:anise/4-anisaldehyde] In perfumery, it is particularly used in hawthorn, lilac, and cherry blossom accords because of its good tenacity.
[src:anise/4-anisaldehyde] It also serves as a key intermediate in the synthesis of the antibiotic amoxicillin.
[src:anise/4-anisaldehyde] A solution of *para*-anisaldehyde in acid and ethanol is a useful stain in thin layer chromatography.
[src:anise/4-anisaldehyde] Different chemical compounds on the plate can give different colors, allowing easy distinction.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe was created in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland in the late 18th century by the French physician Pierre Ordinaire.
[src:anise/absinthe] It rose to great popularity as an alcoholic drink in late 19th- and early 20th-century France, particularly among Parisian artists and writers.
[src:anise/absinthe] The consumption of absinthe was opposed by social conservatives and prohibitionists, partly due to its association with bohemian culture.
[src:anise/absinthe] From Europe and the Americas, notable absinthe drinkers included Ernest Hemingway, James Joyce, Lewis Carroll, Charles Baudelaire, Paul Verlaine, Arthur Rimbaud, and Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe has often been portrayed as a dangerously addictive psychoactive drug and hallucinogen, which gave birth to the term *absinthism*.
[src:anise/absinthe] The chemical compound thujone, which is present in the spirit in trace amounts, was blamed for its alleged harmful effects.
[src:anise/absinthe] By 1915, absinthe had been banned in the United States and much of Europe, including France, the Netherlands, Belgium, Switzerland, and Austria-Hungary, though it has not been demonstrated to be any more dangerous than ordinary spirits.
[src:anise/absinthe] Recent studies have shown that absinthe's psychoactive properties, apart from those attributable to its alcohol content, have been exaggerated.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe's revival began in the 1990s, following the adoption of modern European Union food and beverage laws that removed long-standing barriers to its production and sale.
[src:anise/absinthe] By the early 21st century, nearly 200 brands of absinthe were being produced in a dozen countries, most notably in France, Switzerland, Austria, Germany, the Netherlands, Spain, and the Czech Republic.
[src:anise/absinthe] The French word *absinthe* can refer either to the alcoholic beverage, or less commonly, to the actual wormwood plant.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe is derived from the Latin *absinthium*, which in turn comes from the Greek ἀψίνθιον *apsínthion* 'wormwood'.
[src:anise/absinthe] Some argue that the word means "undrinkable" in Greek, but it may instead be linked to the Persian root, in Persian called *spand* or *aspand* or the variant *esfand*, which meant *Peganum harmala*, also called Syrian rue in English, although it is not a variety of rue, another famously bitter herb.
[src:anise/absinthe] That *Artemisia absinthium* was commonly burned as a protective offering may suggest that its origins lie in the reconstructed Proto-Indo-European language root **spend*, meaning "to perform a ritual" or "make an offering".
[src:anise/absinthe] Whether the word was a borrowing from Persian into Greek, or from a common ancestor of both, is unclear.
[src:anise/absinthe] Alternatively, the Greek word may originate in a pre-Greek substrate word, marked by the non-Indo-European consonant complex -νθ *-nth*.
[src:anise/absinthe] Alternative spellings for absinthe include *absinth*, *absynthe*, and *absenta*.
[src:anise/absinthe] *Absinth* (without the final *e*) is a spelling variant most commonly applied to absinthes produced in central and eastern Europe, and is specifically associated with Bohemian-style absinthes.
[src:anise/absinthe] The precise origin of absinthe is unclear.
[src:anise/absinthe] The medical use of wormwood dates back to ancient Egypt and is mentioned in the Ebers Papyrus from around 1550 BC.
[src:anise/absinthe] Wormwood extracts and wine-soaked wormwood leaves were used as remedies by the ancient Greeks.
[src:anise/absinthe] Moreover, some evidence exists of a wormwood-flavoured wine in ancient Greece called *absinthites oinos*.
[src:anise/absinthe] Lucretius' *De Rerum Natura* (I, 936–950) says that a drink containing wormwood was given as medicine to children in a cup with honey on the brim to make it drinkable.
[src:anise/absinthe] The first evidence of absinthe, in the sense of a distilled spirit containing green anise and fennel, dates to the 18th century.
[src:anise/absinthe] According to popular legend, it began as an all-purpose patent remedy created by Dr.
[src:anise/absinthe] Pierre Ordinaire, a French doctor living in Couvet, Switzerland, around 1792 (the exact date varies by account).
[src:anise/absinthe] Ordinaire's recipe was passed on to the Henriod sisters of Couvet, who sold it as a medicinal elixir.
[src:anise/absinthe] By other accounts, the Henriod sisters may have been making the elixir before Ordinaire's arrival.
[src:anise/absinthe] In either case, a certain Major Dubied acquired the formula from the sisters in 1797 and opened the first absinthe distillery named Dubied Père et Fils in Couvet with his son Marcellin and son-in-law Henry-Louis Pernod.
[src:anise/absinthe] In 1805, they built a second distillery in Pontarlier, France, under the company name Maison Pernod Fils.
[src:anise/absinthe] Pernod Fils remained one of the most popular brands of absinthe until the drink was banned in France in 1914.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe's popularity grew steadily through the 1840s, when it was given to French troops in Algeria as a malaria preventive, and the troops brought home their taste for it.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe became so popular in bars, bistros, cafés, and cabarets by the 1860s that the hour of 5 pm was called *l'heure verte* 'the green hour'.
[src:anise/absinthe] It was favoured by all social classes, from the wealthy bourgeoisie to poor artists and ordinary working-class people.
[src:anise/absinthe] By the 1880s, mass production had caused the price to drop sharply, and the French were drinking 36 million litres (9,500,000 US gal) per year by 1910.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe was exported widely from France and Switzerland and attained some degree of popularity in other countries, including Spain, the United Kingdom, the United States, and the Czech Republic.
[src:anise/absinthe] It was never banned in Spain or Portugal, and its production and consumption have never ceased.
[src:anise/absinthe] It gained a temporary popularity spike during the early 20th century, corresponding with the Art Nouveau and Modernism aesthetic movements.
[src:anise/absinthe] New Orleans has a cultural association with absinthe and is credited as the birthplace of the Sazerac, perhaps the earliest absinthe cocktail.
[src:anise/absinthe] The Old Absinthe House bar on Bourbon Street began selling absinthe in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:anise/absinthe] Its Catalan lease-holder, Cayetano Ferrer, named it the Absinthe Room in 1874 due to the drink's popularity, which was served in the Parisian style.
[src:anise/absinthe] It was frequented by Mark Twain, Oscar Wilde, Franklin Delano Roosevelt, Aleister Crowley, and Frank Sinatra.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe became associated with violent crimes and social disorder, and one modern writer claims that this trend was spurred by fabricated claims and smear campaigns, which he claims were orchestrated by the temperance movement and the wine industry.
[src:anise/absinthe] Edgar Degas's 1876 painting **The Absinthe Drinker** or **Glass of Absinthe** (**L'Absinthe**) can be seen at the Musée d'Orsay epitomising the popular view of absinthe addicts as sodden and benumbed, and Émile Zola described its effects in his novel *L'Assommoir*.
[src:anise/absinthe] In 1905, Swiss farmer Jean Lanfray murdered his wife and two children and then attempted to kill himself after drinking absinthe.
[src:anise/absinthe] Lanfray had drunk a lot of wine and brandy before the killings, but that was overlooked or ignored, and blame for the murders was placed solely on his consumption of two glasses of absinthe.
[src:anise/absinthe] The Lanfray murders were the tipping point in this hotly debated topic, and a subsequent petition collected more than 82,000 signatures to ban it in Switzerland.
[src:anise/absinthe] It was approved by voters, and the prohibition of absinthe was written into the Swiss constitution.
[src:anise/absinthe] In 1906, Belgium and Brazil banned the sale and distribution of absinthe although these were not the first countries to take such action.
[src:anise/absinthe] It had been banned as early as 1898 in the colony of the Congo Free State.
[src:anise/absinthe] The Netherlands banned it in 1909, Switzerland in 1910, the United States in 1912, and France in 1914.
[src:anise/absinthe] The prohibition of absinthe in France eventually led to the popularity of pastis, and to a lesser extent, ouzo, and other anise-flavoured spirits that do not contain wormwood.
[src:anise/absinthe] Following the conclusion of the First World War, production of the Pernod Fils brand was resumed at the Banus distillery in Catalonia, Spain (where absinthe was still legal), but gradually declining sales saw the cessation of production in the 1960s.
[src:anise/absinthe] In Switzerland, the ban served only to drive the production of absinthe underground.
[src:anise/absinthe] Clandestine home distillers produced colourless absinthe (*la Bleue*), which was easier to conceal from the authorities.
[src:anise/absinthe] Many countries never banned absinthe, notably the United Kingdom, where it had never been as popular as in continental Europe.
[src:anise/absinthe] British importer BBH Spirits began to import Hill's Absinth from the Czech Republic in the 1990s, as the UK had never formally banned it, and this sparked a modern resurgence in its popularity.
[src:anise/absinthe] It began to reappear during a revival in the 1990s in countries where it was never banned.
[src:anise/absinthe] Forms of absinthe available during that time consisted almost exclusively of Czech, Spanish, and Portuguese brands that were of recent origin, typically consisting of Bohemian-style products.
[src:anise/absinthe] Connoisseurs considered these of inferior quality and not representative of the 19th-century spirit.
[src:anise/absinthe] In 2000, La Fée Absinthe became the first commercial absinthe distilled and bottled in France since the 1914 ban, but it is now one of dozens of brands that are produced and sold within France.
[src:anise/absinthe] In the Netherlands, the restrictions were challenged by Amsterdam wine seller Menno Boorsma in July 2004, thus confirming the legality of absinthe once again.
[src:anise/absinthe] Similarly, Belgium lifted its long-standing ban on 1 January 2005 citing a conflict with the adopted food and beverage regulations of the single European Market.
[src:anise/absinthe] In Switzerland, the constitutional ban was repealed in 2000 during an overhaul of the national constitution although the prohibition was written into ordinary law instead.
[src:anise/absinthe] That law was later repealed, and absinthe was made legal on March 1, 2005.
[src:anise/absinthe] The drink was never officially banned in Spain although it began to fall out of favour in the 1940s and almost vanished into obscurity.
[src:anise/absinthe] Catalonia has seen a significant resurgence since 2007 when one producer established operations there.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe has never been illegal to import or manufacture in Australia although importation requires a permit under the Customs (Prohibited Imports) Regulation 1956 due to a restriction on importing any product containing oil of wormwood.
[src:anise/absinthe] In 2000, an amendment made all wormwood species prohibited herbs for food purposes under Food Standard 1.4.4.
[src:anise/absinthe] Prohibited and Restricted Plants and Fungi.
[src:anise/absinthe] However, this amendment was found inconsistent with other parts of the pre-existing Food Code, and it was withdrawn in 2002 during the transition between the two codes, thereby continuing to allow absinthe manufacture and importation through the existing permit-based system.
[src:anise/absinthe] These events were erroneously reported by the media as it having been reclassified from a *prohibited* product to a *restricted* product.
[src:anise/absinthe] In 2007, the French brand Lucid became the first genuine absinthe to receive a Certificate of Label Approval for import into the United States since 1912, following independent efforts by representatives from Lucid and Kübler to overturn the long-standing U.S. ban.
[src:anise/absinthe] George Spirits of Alameda, California became the first brand of American-made absinthe produced in the United States since the ban.
[src:anise/absinthe] Since that time, other micro-distilleries have started producing small batches in the United States.
[src:anise/absinthe] The French Absinthe Ban of 1915 was repealed in May 2011 following petitions by the *Fédération Française des Spiritueux*, which represents French distillers, and the French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in April 2011.
[src:anise/absinthe] In Switzerland, the village of Môtiers, Val-de-Travers, near Neuchâtel, became the focal point of production and promotion of the liquor after a ban of nearly 100 years was lifted.
[src:anise/absinthe] The national *Maison de l'Absinthe* (House of Absinthe), with its attached museum, is located in the former courthouse where absinthe distillers were formerly prosecuted.
[src:anise/absinthe] The 21st century has seen new types of absinthe, including various frozen preparations, that have become increasingly popular.
[src:anise/absinthe] Most countries have no legal definition for absinthe, whereas the method of production and content of spirits such as whisky, brandy, and gin are globally defined and regulated.
[src:anise/absinthe] Therefore, producers are at liberty to label a product as "absinthe" or "absinth" without regard to any specific legal definition or quality standards.
[src:anise/absinthe] Producers of legitimate absinthes employ one of two historically defined processes to create the finished spirit – distillation or cold mixing.
[src:anise/absinthe] In the sole country (Switzerland) that does possess a legal definition of absinthe, distillation is the only permitted method of production.
[src:anise/absinthe] Distilled absinthe employs a method of production similar to that of high-quality gin.
[src:anise/absinthe] Botanicals are initially macerated in distilled base alcohol before being redistilled to exclude bitter principles, and impart the desired complexity and texture to the spirit.
[src:anise/absinthe] The distillation of absinthe first yields a colourless distillate that leaves the alembic at around 72% ABV.
[src:anise/absinthe] The distillate may be reduced and bottled clear, to produce a *Blanche* or *la Bleue* absinthe, or it may be coloured to create a *verte* using natural or artificial colouring.
[src:anise/absinthe] Traditional absinthes obtain their green color strictly from the chlorophyll of whole herbs, which is extracted from the plants during the secondary maceration.
[src:anise/absinthe] This step involves steeping plants such as petite wormwood, hyssop, and melissa (among other herbs) in the distillate.
[src:anise/absinthe] Chlorophyll from these herbs is extracted, giving the drink its famous green color.
[src:anise/absinthe] This step also provides a herbal complexity that is typical of high-quality absinthe.
[src:anise/absinthe] The natural coloring process is critical for absinthe ageing since the chlorophyll remains chemically active.
[src:anise/absinthe] The chlorophyll serves a similar role in absinthe as tannins do in wine or brown liquors.
[src:anise/absinthe] After the coloring process, the resulting product is diluted with water to the desired alcohol percentage.
[src:anise/absinthe] The flavor of absinthe is said to improve materially with storage, and many distilleries, before the ban, aged their absinthe in settling tanks before bottling.
[src:anise/absinthe] Many modern absinthes are produced using a cold-mix process.
[src:anise/absinthe] This inexpensive method of production does not involve distillation, and is regarded as inferior for the same reasons that give cause for cheaply compounded gin to be legally differentiated from distilled gin.
[src:anise/absinthe] The cold mixing process involves the simple blending of flavouring essences and artificial colouring in commercial alcohol, in similar fashion to most flavoured vodkas and inexpensive liqueurs and cordials.
[src:anise/absinthe] Some modern cold-mixed absinthes have been bottled at strengths approaching 90% ABV.
[src:anise/absinthe] Others are presented simply as a bottle of plain alcohol with a small amount of powdered herbs suspended within it.
[src:anise/absinthe] The lack of a formal legal definition in most countries to regulate the production and quality of absinthe has enabled cheaply made products to be falsely presented as traditional in production and composition.
[src:anise/absinthe] In Switzerland, the only country with a formal legal definition of absinthe, any absinthe product not obtained by maceration and distillation or coloured artificially cannot be sold as absinthe.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe is traditionally prepared from a distillation of neutral alcohol, various herbs, spices, and water.
[src:anise/absinthe] Traditional absinthes were redistilled from a white grape spirit (or *eau de vie*), while lesser absinthes were more commonly made from alcohol from grains, beets, or potatoes.
[src:anise/absinthe] The principal botanicals are grande wormwood, green anise, and florence fennel, which are often called "the holy trinity".
[src:anise/absinthe] Many other herbs may be used as well, such as petite wormwood (*Artemisia pontica* or Roman wormwood), hyssop, melissa, star anise, angelica, peppermint, coriander, and veronica.
[src:anise/absinthe] One early recipe was included in 1864's *The English and Australian Cookery Book*.
[src:anise/absinthe] It directed the maker to "Take of the tops of wormwood, four pounds; root of angelica, calamus aromaticus, aniseed, leaves of dittany, of each one ounce; alcohol, four gallons.
[src:anise/absinthe] Macerate these substances during eight days, add a little water, and distil by a gentle fire, until two gallons are obtained.
[src:anise/absinthe] Adding to absinthe's negative reputation in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, unscrupulous makers of the drink omitted the traditional colouring phase of production in favour of adding toxic copper salts to artificially induce a green tint.
[src:anise/absinthe] This practice may be responsible for some of the alleged toxicity historically associated with this beverage.
[src:anise/absinthe] Many modern-day producers resort to other shortcuts, including the use of artificial food coloring to create the green color.
[src:anise/absinthe] Additionally, at least some cheap absinthes produced before the ban were reportedly adulterated with poisonous antimony trichloride, reputed to enhance the louching effect.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe may also be naturally coloured pink or red using rose or hibiscus flowers.
[src:anise/absinthe] This was referred to as a *rose* (pink) or *rouge* (red) absinthe.
[src:anise/absinthe] Only one historical brand of rose absinthe has been documented.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe was historically bottled at 45–74% ABV.
[src:anise/absinthe] Some modern Franco–Suisse absinthes are bottled at up to 83% ABV, while some modern, cold-mixed bohemian-style absinthes are bottled at up to 89.9% ABV.
[src:anise/absinthe] The modern-day interest in absinthe has spawned a rash of absinthe kits from sellers claiming they produce homemade absinthe.
[src:anise/absinthe] Kits often call for soaking herbs in vodka or alcohol or adding a liquid concentrate to vodka or alcohol to create an ersatz absinthe.
[src:anise/absinthe] Such practices usually yield a harsh substance that bears little resemblance to the genuine article and is considered inauthentic by any practical standard.
[src:anise/absinthe] Some concoctions may even be dangerous, especially if they call for a potentially poisonous inclusion of herbs, oils, or extracts.
[src:anise/absinthe] In at least one documented case, a person suffered acute kidney injury after drinking 10 ml of pure wormwood oil.
[src:anise/absinthe] In baking and in preparing the classic New Orleans-style Sazerac cocktail, anise-flavored liqueurs and pastis have often been used as a substitute if absinthe is unavailable.
[src:anise/absinthe] The traditional French preparation involves placing a sugar cube on top of a specially designed slotted spoon and placing the spoon on a glass filled with a measure of absinthe.
[src:anise/absinthe] Iced water is poured or dripped over the sugar cube to mix the water into the absinthe.
[src:anise/absinthe] The final preparation contains 1 part absinthe and 3–5 parts water.
[src:anise/absinthe] As water dilutes the spirit, those components with poor water solubility (mainly those from anise, fennel, and star anise) come out of solution and cloud the drink.
[src:anise/absinthe] The resulting milky opalescence is called the *louche* (/luʃ/, French: 'opaque' or 'shady').
[src:anise/absinthe] The release of these dissolved essences coincides with a perfuming of herbal aromas and flavours that "blossom" or "bloom", and brings out subtleties that are otherwise muted within the neat spirit.
[src:anise/absinthe] This reflects what is perhaps the oldest and purest method of preparation, and is often referred to as the *French method*.
[src:anise/absinthe] The *Bohemian method* is a recent invention that involves fire, and was not performed during absinthe's peak of popularity in the Belle Époque.
[src:anise/absinthe] Like the French method, a sugar cube is placed on a slotted spoon over a glass containing one shot of absinthe.
[src:anise/absinthe] The sugar is soaked in alcohol (usually more absinthe), and then set ablaze.
[src:anise/absinthe] The flaming sugar cube is then dropped into the glass, thus igniting the absinthe.
[src:anise/absinthe] Finally, a shot glass of water is added to douse the flames.
[src:anise/absinthe] This method tends to produce a stronger drink than the French method.
[src:anise/absinthe] A variant of the Bohemian method involves allowing the fire to extinguish on its own.
[src:anise/absinthe] This variant is sometimes referred to as "cooking the absinthe" or "the flaming green fairy".
[src:anise/absinthe] The origin of this burning ritual may borrow from a coffee and brandy drink that was served at Café Brûlot, in which a sugar cube soaked in brandy was set aflame.
[src:anise/absinthe] Most experienced absintheurs do not recommend the Bohemian Method and consider it a modern gimmick, as it can destroy the absinthe flavour and present a fire hazard due to the unusually high alcohol content present in absinthe.
[src:anise/absinthe] In 19th-century Parisian cafés, upon receiving an order for absinthe, a waiter would present the patron with a dose of absinthe in a suitable glass, sugar, absinthe spoon, and a carafe of iced water.
[src:anise/absinthe] It was up to the patron to prepare the drink, as the inclusion or omission of sugar was strictly an individual preference, as was the amount of water used.
[src:anise/absinthe] As the popularity of the drink increased, additional accoutrements of preparation appeared, including the absinthe fountain, which was effectively a large jar of iced water with spigots, mounted on a lamp base.
[src:anise/absinthe] This lets drinkers prepare several drinks at once – and with a hands-free drip, patrons could socialise while louching a glass.
[src:anise/absinthe] Although many bars served absinthe in standard glassware, several glasses were specifically designed for the French absinthe preparation ritual.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe glasses were typically fashioned with a dose line, bulge, or bubble in the lower portion denoting how much absinthe should be poured.
[src:anise/absinthe] One "dose" of absinthe ranged anywhere around 2–2.5 fluid ounces (60–75 ml).
[src:anise/absinthe] In addition to being prepared with sugar and water, absinthe emerged as a popular cocktail ingredient in both the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:anise/absinthe] By 1930, dozens of fancy cocktails that called for absinthe had been published in numerous credible bartender guides.
[src:anise/absinthe] One of the most famous of these libations is Ernest Hemingway's "Death in the Afternoon" cocktail, a tongue-in-cheek concoction that contributed to a 1935 collection of celebrity recipes.
[src:anise/absinthe] The directions are: "Pour one jigger absinthe into a Champagne glass.
[src:anise/absinthe] Add iced Champagne until it attains the proper opalescent milkiness.
[src:anise/absinthe] Most categorical alcoholic beverages have regulations governing their classification and labelling, while those governing absinthe have always been conspicuously lacking.
[src:anise/absinthe] According to popular treatises from the 19th century, absinthe could be loosely categorised into several grades (*ordinaire*, *demi-fine*, *fine*, and *Suisse* – the latter does not denote origin), in order of increasing alcoholic strength and quality.
[src:anise/absinthe] Many contemporary absinthe critics simply classify absinthe as *distilled* or *mixed*, according to its production method.
[src:anise/absinthe] And while the former is generally considered far superior in quality to the latter, an absinthe's simple claim of being 'distilled' makes no guarantee as to the quality of its base ingredients or the skill of its maker.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe that is artificially coloured or clear is aesthetically stable and can be bottled in clear glass.
[src:anise/absinthe] If naturally colored absinthe is exposed to light or air for a prolonged period, the chlorophyll gradually becomes oxidized, which has the effect of gradually changing the color from green to yellow green, and eventually to brown.
[src:anise/absinthe] The colour of absinthe that has completed this transition was historically referred to as *feuille morte* ("dead leaf").
[src:anise/absinthe] In the pre-ban era, this natural phenomenon was favourably viewed, for it confirmed the product in question was coloured naturally, and not artificially with potentially toxic chemicals.
[src:anise/absinthe] Predictably, vintage absinthes often emerge from sealed bottles as distinctly amber in tint due to decades of slow oxidation.
[src:anise/absinthe] Though this colour change presents no adverse impact to the flavour of absinthe, it is generally desired to preserve the original colour, which requires that naturally coloured absinthe be bottled in dark, light-resistant bottles.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe intended for decades of storage should be kept in a cool (room temperature), dry place, away from light and heat.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe should not be stored in the refrigerator or freezer, as the anethole may polymerise inside the bottle, creating an irreversible precipitate, and adversely impacting the original flavour.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe has been frequently described in modern times as being hallucinogenic, a claim refuted by modern science.
[src:anise/absinthe] The belief that absinthe induces hallucinogenic effects is rooted, at least partly, in the findings of 19th-century French psychiatrist Valentin Magnan, who carried out ten years of experiments with wormwood oil.
[src:anise/absinthe] In the course of this research, he studied 250 cases of alcoholism and concluded that those who abused absinthe were worse off than those who abused other alcoholic drinks, experiencing rapid-onset hallucinations.
[src:anise/absinthe] Such accounts by opponents of absinthe (like Magnan) were cheerfully embraced by famous absinthe drinkers, many of whom were bohemian artists or writers.
[src:anise/absinthe] Two famous artists who helped popularise the notion that absinthe had powerful psychoactive properties were Toulouse-Lautrec and Vincent van Gogh.
[src:anise/absinthe] In one of the best-known written accounts of absinthe drinking, an inebriated Oscar Wilde described a phantom sensation of having tulips brush against his legs after leaving a bar at closing time.
[src:anise/absinthe] Notions of absinthe's alleged hallucinogenic properties were again fuelled in the 1970s when a scientific paper suggested that thujone's structural similarity to tetrahydrocannabinol (THC), the active chemical in cannabis, presented the possibility of THC receptor affinity.
[src:anise/absinthe] Counterevidence to this was published in 1999.
[src:anise/absinthe] The debate over whether absinthe produces effects on the human mind in addition to those of alcohol has not been resolved conclusively.
[src:anise/absinthe] The effects of absinthe have been described by some as mind-opening.
[src:anise/absinthe] The most commonly reported experience is a "clear-headed" feeling of inebriation – a form of "lucid drunkenness".
[src:anise/absinthe] Chemist, historian, and absinthe distiller Ted Breaux has claimed that the alleged secondary effects of absinthe may be because some of the herbal compounds in the drink act as stimulants, while others act as sedatives, creating an overall lucid effect of awakening.
[src:anise/absinthe] The long-term effects of moderate absinthe consumption in humans remain unknown, although herbs traditionally used to produce absinthe are reported to have both painkilling and antiparasitic properties.
[src:anise/absinthe] Today it is known that absinthe does not cause hallucinations.
[src:anise/absinthe] It was once widely promoted that excessive absinthe drinking caused effects that were discernible from those associated with alcoholism, a belief that led to the coining of the term *absinthism*.
[src:anise/absinthe] One of the first vilifications of absinthe followed an 1864 experiment in which Magnan simultaneously exposed one guinea pig to large doses of pure wormwood vapour, and another to alcohol vapours.
[src:anise/absinthe] The guinea pig exposed to wormwood vapour experienced convulsive seizures, while the animal exposed to alcohol did not.
[src:anise/absinthe] Magnan would later blame the naturally occurring (in wormwood) chemical thujone for these effects.
[src:anise/absinthe] Thujone, once widely believed to be an active chemical in absinthe, is a GABA antagonist, and while it can produce muscle spasms in large doses, there is no direct evidence to suggest it causes hallucinations.
[src:anise/absinthe] Past reports estimated thujone concentrations in absinthe as being up to 260 mg/kg.
[src:anise/absinthe] As such, most traditionally crafted absinthes, both vintage and modern, fall within the current EU standards.
[src:anise/absinthe] Tests conducted on mice to study toxicity showed an oral LD50 of about 45 mg thujone per kg of body weight, which represents far more absinthe than could be realistically consumed.
[src:anise/absinthe] The high percentage of alcohol in absinthe would result in mortality long before thujone could become a factor.
[src:anise/absinthe] In documented cases of acute thujone poisoning as a result of oral ingestion, the source of thujone was not commercial absinthe, but rather non-absinthe-related sources, such as common essential oils (which may contain as much as 50% thujone).
[src:anise/absinthe] One study published in the *Journal of Studies on Alcohol* concluded that high doses (0.28 mg/kg) of thujone in alcohol had negative effects on attention performance in a clinical setting.
[src:anise/absinthe] It delayed reaction time, and caused subjects to concentrate their attention on the central field of vision.
[src:anise/absinthe] Low doses (0.028 mg/kg) did not produce an effect noticeably different from the plain alcohol control.
[src:anise/absinthe] While the effects of the high dose samples were statistically significant in a double blind test, the test subjects themselves were unable to reliably identify which samples contained thujone.
[src:anise/absinthe] For the average 65 kg (143 lb) man, the high dose samples in the study would equate to 18.2 mg of thujone.
[src:anise/absinthe] The EU limit of 35 mg/L of thujone in absinthe means that given the highest permitted thujone content, that individual would need to consume approximately 0.5 litres of high-proof (e.g.
[src:anise/absinthe] 50%+ ABV) spirit before the thujone could be metabolized to display effects detectable in a clinical setting, which would result in a potentially lethal BAC of >0.4%.
[src:anise/absinthe] Most countries (except Switzerland) at present do not possess a legal definition of absinthe (unlike Scotch whisky or cognac).
[src:anise/absinthe] Accordingly, producers are free to label a product "absinthe" or "absinth", whether or not it bears any resemblance to the traditional spirit.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe is readily available in many bottle shops.
[src:anise/absinthe] Bitters may contain a maximum 35 mg/kg thujone, while other alcoholic beverages can contain a maximum 10 mg/kg.
[src:anise/absinthe] The domestic production and sale of absinthe is regulated by state licensing laws.
[src:anise/absinthe] These controls have now been repealed, and permission is no longer required.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe was prohibited in Brazil until 1999 and was brought by entrepreneur Lalo Zanini and legalised in the same year.
[src:anise/absinthe] Presently, absinthe sold in Brazil must abide by the national law that restricts all spirits to a maximum of 54% ABV.
[src:anise/absinthe] While this regulation is enforced throughout channels of legal distribution, it may be possible to find absinthe containing alcohol in excess of the legal limit in some restaurants or food fairs.
[src:anise/absinthe] In Canada, liquor laws concerning the production, distribution, and sale of spirits are written and enforced by individual provincial government monopolies.
[src:anise/absinthe] Each product is subject to the approval of a respective individual provincial liquor board before it can be sold in that province.
[src:anise/absinthe] Importation is a federal matter and is enforced by the Canada Border Services Agency.
[src:anise/absinthe] The importation of a nominal amount of liquor by individuals for personal use is permitted, provided that conditions for the individual's duration of stay outside the country are satisfied.
[src:anise/absinthe] In 2007, Canada's first genuine absinthe (Taboo Absinthe) was created by Okanagan Spirits Craft Distillery in British Columbia.
[src:anise/absinthe] The European Union permits a maximum thujone level of 35 mg/kg in alcoholic beverages where *Artemisia* species is a listed ingredient, and 10 mg/kg in other alcoholic beverages.
[src:anise/absinthe] Member countries regulate absinthe production within this framework.
[src:anise/absinthe] The sale of absinthe is permitted in all EU countries unless they further regulate it.
[src:anise/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe was prohibited in Finland from 1919 to 1932; no current prohibitions exist.
[src:anise/absinthe] The government-owned chain of liquor stores (Alko) is the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing over 8% ABV, although national law bans the sale of alcoholic beverages containing over 80% ABV.
[src:anise/absinthe] Édouard Manet's first major painting *The Absinthe Drinker* was controversial, and was rejected by the Paris Salon in 1859.
[src:anise/absinthe] French producers circumvented this regulatory obstacle by labelling absinthe as *spiritueux à base de plantes d'absinthe* ('wormwood-based spirits'), with many either reducing or omitting fennel and hyssop altogether from their products.
[src:anise/absinthe] A legal challenge to the scientific basis of this decree resulted in its repeal (2009), which opened the door for the official French re-legalisation of absinthe for the first time since 1915.
[src:anise/absinthe] The French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in mid-April 2011.
[src:anise/absinthe] A ban on absinthe was enacted in Germany on 27 March 1923.
[src:anise/absinthe] In addition to banning the production of commercial trade in absinthe, the law went so far as to prohibit the distribution of printed matter that provided details of its production.
[src:anise/absinthe] The original ban was lifted in 1981, but the use of *Artemisia absinthium* as a flavouring agent remained prohibited.
[src:anise/absinthe] On 27 September 1991, Germany adopted the European Community's standards of 1988, which effectively re-legalised absinthe.
[src:anise/absinthe] The Fascist regime in 1926 banned the production, import, transport, and sale of any liquor named *Assenzio*.
[src:anise/absinthe] The ban was reinforced in 1931 with harsher penalties for transgressors and remained in force until 1992 when the Italian government amended its laws to comply with the EU directive 88/388/EEC.
[src:anise/absinthe] Although absinthe is not prohibited at the national level, some local authorities have banned it.
[src:anise/absinthe] The ban came in August 2008 after several issues of misuse drew public and police attention.
[src:anise/absinthe] One incident resulted in breathing difficulties and hospitalising of a 17-year-old for alcohol poisoning.
[src:anise/absinthe] The particular brand of absinthe that caused these effects was bottled at 89% ABV.
[src:anise/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe has never been prohibited in Sweden or Norway.
[src:anise/absinthe] However, the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing more than 3.5% ABV in Sweden and 4.75% ABV in Norway is the government-owned chain of liquor stores known as Systembolaget in Sweden and Vinmonopolet in Norway.
[src:anise/absinthe] Systembolaget and Vinmonopolet did not import or sell absinthe for many years after the ban in France; however, today several absinthes are available for purchase in Systembolaget stores, including Swedish made distilled absinthe.
[src:anise/absinthe] In Norway, on the other hand, one is less likely to find many absinthes since Norwegian alcohol law prohibits the sale and importation of alcoholic beverages above 60% ABV, which eliminates most absinthes.
[src:anise/absinthe] In Switzerland, the sale and production of absinthe was prohibited from 1910 to 1 March 2005.
[src:anise/absinthe] This was based on a vote in 1908, inspired by the Jean Lanfray incident.
[src:anise/absinthe] To be legally made or sold in Switzerland, absinthe must be distilled, must not contain certain additives, and must be either naturally coloured or left uncoloured.
[src:anise/absinthe] In 2014, the Federal Administrative Court of Switzerland invalidated a governmental decision of 2010 which allowed only absinthe made in the Val-de-Travers region to be labelled as absinthe in Switzerland.
[src:anise/absinthe] The court found that absinthe was a label for a product and was not tied to a geographic origin.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe was never legally prohibited in the UK, but was not imported for a 70-year period.
[src:anise/absinthe] In 2007, the Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau (TTB) effectively lifted the long-standing absinthe ban, and it has since approved many brands for sale in the US market.
[src:anise/absinthe] This was made possible partly through the TTB's clarification of the Food and Drug Administration's (FDA) thujone content regulations, which specify that finished food and beverages that contain *Artemisia* species must be thujone-free.
[src:anise/absinthe] In this context, the TTB considers a product thujone-free if the thujone content is less than 10 ppm (equal to 10 mg/kg).
[src:anise/absinthe] This is verified through the use of gas chromatography–mass spectrometry.
[src:anise/absinthe] The brands Kübler and Lucid and their lawyers did most of the work to get absinthe legalized in the U.S., over the 2004–2007 time period.
[src:anise/absinthe] In the U.S., 5 March sometimes is referred to as "National Absinthe Day", as it was the day the 95-year ban on absinthe was finally lifted.
[src:anise/absinthe] Absinthe imported in violation of these regulations is subject to seizure at the discretion of U.S.
[src:anise/absinthe] Numerous artists and writers living in France in the late 19th and early 20th centuries were noted absinthe drinkers and featured absinthe in their work.
[src:anise/absinthe] Some of these included Édouard Manet, Guy de Maupassant, Paul Verlaine, Amedeo Modigliani, Edgar Degas, Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, Vincent van Gogh, Oscar Wilde, Arthur Rimbaud, and Émile Zola.
[src:anise/absinthe] Many other renowned artists and writers similarly drew from this cultural well, including Aleister Crowley, Ernest Hemingway, Pablo Picasso, August Strindberg, and Erik Satie.
[src:anise/absinthe] The aura of illicitness and mystery surrounding absinthe has played into literature, movies, music, and television, where it is often portrayed as a mysterious, addictive, and mind-altering drink.
[src:anise/absinthe] Marie Corelli's *Wormwood: A Drama of Paris* (1890) was a popular novel about a Frenchman driven to murder and ruin after being introduced to absinthe.
[src:anise/absinthe] Intended as a morality tale on the dangers of the drink, it was speculated to have contributed to subsequent bans of absinthe in Europe and the United States.
[src:anise/absinthe] Some of the earliest film references include *The Hasher's Delirium* (1910) by Émile Cohl, an early pioneer in the art of animation, as well as two different silent films, each titled *Absinthe*, from 1913 and 1914 respectively.
[src:anise/absinthe] More recently, it served as the title of a 2018 song by the indie group I Don't Know How But They Found Me.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The plant is native to temperate regions of Eurasia and North America.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] It has been introduced as feed for livestock in New Zealand and Australia.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] It has some potential uses, including in traditional medicine.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The inflorescence has 4 to 9 phyllaries and contains ray and disk flowers which are white to pink, blooming from March to October.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] There are generally 3 to 8 ray flowers, which are 3 millimetres (1⁄8 in) long and ovate to round.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The tiny disk flowers range from 10 to 40.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The inflorescence is produced in a flat-topped capitulum cluster and the inflorescences are visited by many insect species, and has a generalized pollination system.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The small achene-like fruits are called cypsela.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The plant has a distinct spicy scent that persists when dried and may be irritating to some.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The dark blue essential oil of yarrow contains chemicals called proazulenes.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Chamazulene and δ-cadinol are chemical compounds found in *A. millefolium*.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The chromophore of azulene was discovered in yarrow and wormwood and named in 1863 by Septimus Piesse.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Yarrow contains isovaleric acid, salicylic acid, asparagine, sterols, and flavonoids.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The genus name *Achillea* (Latin for 'Achillean') is derived from mythical Greek character Achilles who, by legend, carried it with his army to treat battle wounds.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The specific epithet *millefolium* (Latin for 'thousand-leaves') comes from the featherlike leaves which are minutely divided.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Yarrow is native to temperate regions of the Northern Hemisphere, being found in Europe, Asia, and North America.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The plant grows from sea level to 3,500 m (11,500 ft) in elevation.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Common yarrow is frequently found in the mildly disturbed soil of grasslands and open forests.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] In North America, both native and introduced genotypes, and both diploid and polyploid plants are found.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] It is found in every habitat throughout California except the Colorado and Mojave Deserts.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Common yarrow produces an average yield of 110,000 plants per hectare (43,000/acre), with a total dry weight of 11,800 kg/ha (10,500 pounds per acre).
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] It has been introduced as a feed for livestock in New Zealand and Australia, where it is a common weed of both wet and dry areas, such as roadsides, meadows, fields and coastal places.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Several cavity-nesting birds, including the common starling, use yarrow to line their nests.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Experiments conducted on the tree swallow, which does not use yarrow, suggest that adding yarrow to nests inhibits the growth of parasites.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] For propagation, seeds require light for germination, so optimal germination occurs when planted no deeper than 6 mm (1⁄4 in).
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Seeds also require a germination temperature of 18–24 °C (64–75 °F).
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] It has a relatively short life in some situations, but may be prolonged by division in the spring every other year, and planting 30 to 46 cm (12–18 in) apart.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The species use in traditional gardens has generally been superseded by cultivars with specific 'improved' qualities.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Some are used as drought-tolerant lawns, with periodic mowing.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The many different ornamental cultivars include: 'Paprika', 'Cerise Queen', 'Red Beauty', 'Red Velvet', 'Saucy Seduction', 'Strawberry Seduction' (red), 'Island Pink' (pink), 'Calistoga' (white), and 'Sonoma Coast' (white).
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The many hybrids of this species designated *Achillea* × *taygetea* are useful garden subjects, including: 'Appleblossom', 'Fanal', 'Hoffnung', and 'Moonshine'.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] According to the American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals, yarrow is toxic to dogs, cats, and horses, causing increased urination, vomiting, diarrhea and dermatitis.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] When consumed by cows, an unfavorable flavor is given to their milk.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] North American varieties were traditionally used by many Native American nations.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The Navajo considered it a "life medicine" and chewed the plant for toothaches and used its infusions for earaches.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The Miwok in California used the plant as an analgesic and head cold remedy.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Native American nations used the plant for healing cuts and abrasions, relief from earaches and throat infections, as well as for an eyewash.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Yarrow was used by Plains indigenous peoples to reduce pain or fever and aid sleep.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Some Ojibwe people used a decoction of yarrow leaves on hot stones and inhaled it to treat headaches, or applied decoctions of the root onto skin for its stimulating effect.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The entire plant is reportedly edible and nutritious, but it is advised not to consume much.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The foliage is pungent; both its leaves and flowers are bitter and astringent.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The leaves can be eaten young; raw, they can be added to salad.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The leaves, with an aniseed-grass flavor, can be brewed as tea.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] In the Middle Ages, yarrow was part of a herbal mixture known as gruit used in the flavoring of beer prior to the use of hops.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] However, medieval Dutch and German city accounts from the gruit area do not mention yarrow.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] It is noted by the Swedish biologist Linnaeus that the Dalecarnians infused the herb in beer.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The flowers and leaves are still used in making some liquors and bitters.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Yarrow is used as a companion plant, attracting some beneficial insects and repelling some pests.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Yarrow can be used for dying wool; depending on the mordant, the color may be green to yellow.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Yarrow has been found with Neanderthal burials, suggesting its association with human species dates to at least 60,000 years ago.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Yarrow and tortoiseshell are considered to be lucky in Chinese tradition.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Dried yarrow stalks are used in I Ching divination.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] In antiquity, the plant was known as **herba militaris** for its use in stanching the flow of blood from wounds.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] In the Classical Greek epic *Iliad*, Homer tells of the centaur Chiron, who conveyed herbal secrets to his human pupils and taught Achilles to use yarrow on the battlegrounds of Troy.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The genus name *Achillea* is inspired by the alleged use of the herb by Achilles to treat his soldiers' wounds.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Other names implying the plant's historical use in healing—particularly in the military—include **bloodwort**, **knight's milfoil**, **staunchweed**, and, from its use in the United States Civil War, **soldier's woundwort**.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Its use in either starting or stopping nosebleeds led to the common name **nosebleed**.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The English name **yarrow** comes from its Saxon (Old English) name *gearwe*, which is related to both the Dutch word *gerw* (alternately *yerw*) and the Old High German word *garawa*.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] In the eastern counties it may be called **yarroway**.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] It was called **old man's pepper** due to its pungent flavor, while the name **field hop** came from its use in beer making in Sweden.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] In the Hebrides, a leaf held against the eyes was sometimes believed to give second sight.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] In the witchcraft trial of Elspeth Reoch in March 1616, she was alleged to have plucked "melefour", thought to be another name for yarrow, and said "*In nomine Patris, Fiili, et Spiritus Sancti*" to become able to cure distemper (disorders of the four humours) and impart the faculty of prediction.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] For its association with the Abrahamic devil it was called **bad man's plaything**, **devil's nettle**, and **devil's plaything**.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Yarrow was thought to bring luck due to being, according to one woman cited by James Britten (c.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] 1878), "the first herb our Saviour put in His hand when a child".
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] This is apparently a corruption of the Achilles myth in which Jesus uses the plant to heal his adoptive father.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] For this reason, in France, it was called **herbe de St.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Joseph**, and it has also been called **carpenter's weed** in this regard.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] Various other common names include **arrowroot**, **death flower**, **eerie**, **hundred-leaved grass**, **knyghten**, **old man's mustard**, **sanguinary**, **seven-year's love**, **snake's grass**, and **soldier**.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] The names **milfoil** and **thousand leaf** come refer to the minutely divided leaves.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] In Spanish, it is known as **gordaldo** and, in New Mexico and southern Colorado, **plumajillo** (Spanish for 'little feather').
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] In Sussex and Devonshire superstition, yarrow was used for finding one's real sweetheart.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] so in a dream this night, I hope, my true love will appear.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] and go to sleep with the yarrow under the pillow.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] then retire for the night without speaking and go to sleep with an ounce of yarrow sewn in flannel under the pillow.
[src:anise/achillea-millefolium] If my love do love me, 'twill bleed every drop.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] This herbaceous perennial grows to a height of 1 metre (3+1⁄2 ft) from underground rhizomes.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] The stems are erect, hollow, and grooved.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] The upper leaves are ternate, broad and toothed.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] Numerous flowers are grouped together in an umbrella-shaped flowerhead known as a compound umbel.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] This is divided into several individual umbels (known as umbellets).
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] Each umbellet has 15 to 20 rays (pedicels) that are each topped with a single, small, five-petaled white flower.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] These are visited by many types of pollinating insects.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] The fruits, produced in late summer and autumn, are small and have long curved styles.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] In Eurasia, it is used as a food plant by the larvae of some species of Lepidoptera, including dot moth, grey dagger and grey pug, although *A. podagraria* is not the exclusive host to any of these species.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] Seed dispersal and seedling establishment are typically limited by shading, and new establishments from seed are restricted to disturbed areas.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] However *A. podagraria* readily spreads over large areas of ground by underground rhizomes.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] Once established, the plants are highly competitive, even in shaded environments, and can reduce the diversity of ground cover and prevent the establishment of tree and shrub seedlings.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] Because of its limited seed dispersal ability, short-lived seed bank and seedling recruitment, the primary vector for dispersal to new areas is human plantings as an ornamental, medicinal or vegetable plant, as well as by accidentally spreading rhizomes by dumping of garden waste.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] It spreads rapidly under favorable growing conditions.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] Because of this it has been described as a nuisance species, and been labelled one of the "worst" garden weeds in perennial flower gardens.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] Once established, goutweed is difficult to eradicate.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] The smallest piece of rhizome left in the ground will quickly form a sturdy new plant.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] All-green goutweed may be more persistent and spread more rapidly than ornamental, variegated goutweed varieties, making the all-green type particularly difficult to control.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] And all-green, wild type forms are known to reappear from seeds of variegated varieties.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] Integrative management strategies that combine herbicide with landscape cloth, bark mulch, and hand weeding to control goutweed in a garden are largely unsuccessful because sprouting occurs from either rhizomes or root fragments left in the soil.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] Hand pulling, raking, and digging followed by monitoring to control goutweed may be effective; however, caution must be taken to remove the entire rhizome and root system.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] Removing flowers before seed set may help control the spread of goutweed.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] Because goutweed's starch reserves are typically depleted by spring, removal of leaves in spring could be effective in starving the plant.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] Once goutweed has been removed, the patch should be carefully monitored periodically for a few years.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] New shoots should be dug up and destroyed.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] Revegetation with other plant materials is recommended.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] Systemic herbicides such as glyphosate are recommended because *A. podagraria* will regrow if merely defoliated.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] The most effective means of control is to prevent its establishment in natural communities.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] It is thus recommended to plant goutweed only on sites not adjacent to wildlands and in gardens where root spread can be restricted (e.g., between a sidewalk and a house).
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] However, the aggressive nature of this plant makes even this strategy risky.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] Several states have banned sales of goutweed (also known as bishop's weed).
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] The tender leaves can be utilized as a spring leaf vegetable akin to spinach, having been used thus since antiquity.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] Young leaves are preferred as a pot herb.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] It is best picked from when it appears (as early as February in the UK and other parts of northern Europe) to just before it flowers (May to June).
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] If it is picked after this point it tastes pungent and has a laxative effect.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] However, it can be stopped from flowering by pinching out the flowers, ensuring the plant remains edible if used more sparingly as a pot herb.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] It has been used as a medicinal herb to treat gout and arthritis.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] The plant is said to have been introduced into Great Britain by the Romans as a food plant and into Northern Europe as a medicinal herb by monks.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] It is still found growing in patches surrounding many monastic ruins in Europe, and descriptions of its use are found among monastic writings, such as in *Physica* by Hildegard von Bingen.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] As a member of Apiaceae, its flowers may be confused with extremely toxic species such as poison hemlock and hemlock water dropwort; attention to the leaves is required for a conclusive identification.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] A variegated form is grown as an ornamental plant.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] However it is banned in several states owing to its invasiveness.
[src:anise/aegopodium-podagraria] Seeds from the variegated form may revert to the more aggressive green form.
[src:anise/aframomum-corrorima] The spice, known as **Ethiopian cardamom**, **false cardamom**, or ***korarima***, is obtained from the plant's seeds (usually dried), and is extensively used in Ethiopian and Eritrean cuisine.
[src:anise/aframomum-corrorima] It is an ingredient in *berbere*, *mitmita*, *awaze*, and other spice mixtures, and is also used to flavor coffee.
[src:anise/aframomum-corrorima] Its flavor is comparable to that of the closely related *Elettaria cardamomum* or green cardamom.
[src:anise/aframomum-corrorima] In Ethiopian herbal medicine, the seeds are used as a tonic, carminative, and laxative.
[src:anise/aframomum-corrorima] The plant is native to Tanzania, western Ethiopia (in the vicinity of Lake Tana and Gelemso), southwestern Sudan, western Uganda.
[src:anise/aframomum-corrorima] It is cultivated in both Ethiopia and Eritrea, although the fruits are typically harvested from wild plants.
[src:anise/aframomum-corrorima] The dried fruits are widely sold in markets and are relatively expensive, while fresh fruits are sold in production areas.
[src:anise/aframomum-corrorima] In dried seeds and pods, the major oil components are 1,8-cineole (eucalyptol) and (E)-nerolidol.
[src:anise/aframomum-corrorima] In fresh seeds, the major component of the essential oil is 1,8-cineole, followed by sabinene and geraniol.
[src:anise/aframomum-corrorima] In fresh pods, the major oil constituents are *γ*-terpinene, *β*-pinene, *α*-phellandrene, 1,8-cineole, and *p*-cymene.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] In 2002, Didukh and Wasser correctly rejected the name *A. blazei* for this species, but called the Brazilian fungus *A. brasiliensis*, a name that had already been used for a different species, *Agaricus brasiliensis* Fr.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] Richard Kerrigan undertook genetic and interfertility testing on several fungal strains, and showed that samples of the Brazilian strains called *A. blazei* and *A. brasiliensis* were genetically similar to, and interfertile with, North American populations of *Agaricus subrufescens*.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] These tests also found European samples called *A. rufotegulis* to be of the same species.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] Because *A. subrufescens* is the oldest name, it has taxonomical priority.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] The cap is initially hemispherical, later becoming convex, with a diameter of 5 to 25 centimetres (2 to 10 inches).
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] The color of the cap may range from white to grayish or dull reddish brown; it stains yellow in KOH.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] Its surface is covered with silk-like fibers, although in maturity it develops small scales (squamulose).
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] The cap margin typically splits with age.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] The flesh is white, and has the taste of "green nuts", with the odor of almonds.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] The gills are not attached to the stalk (free), narrow, and crowded closely together.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] They start out whitish in color, then later pinkish, and finally black-brown as the spores mature.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] The spores are ellipsoid, smooth, dark purplish-brown when viewed microscopically, with dimensions of 5.5–7 by 4–5 μm.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] The stipe is 6 to 15 cm (2+1⁄2 to 6 in) long and 1 to 4 cm (1⁄2 to 1+1⁄2 in) thick, and sometimes bulbous at the base.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] Initially solid, the stipe becomes hollow with age; it is cottony (floccose) to scaly toward the base.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] The annulus is abundant and double-layered; it is bent downward toward the stem, smooth and whitish on the upper side, and covered with cottony scales on the lower side.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] A type of ergostane-type compounds called blazeispirols have been isolated from *A. subrufescens*.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] It resembles some related species, including *A. hondensis*.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] Preliminary research indicates *Agaricus* products may have toxic effects on liver function marked by increased serum level of liver enzymes, especially in people with ovarian cancer, and may cause allergic reactions.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] Contrary to concerns about possible hepatotoxicity, multiple peer-reviewed studies suggest that *A. subrufescens* (*A. blazei* Murill) exhibits hepatoprotective effects rather than toxicity in both human and animal models.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] Food and Drug Administration has issued warning letters to companies marketing *Agaricus* supplement products with unproven health claims of suggesting disease treatment or prevention, but these actions were based on regulatory compliance and not on evidence of toxicity.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] The mushroom is edible for most people, with a somewhat sweet taste and an almond aroma resulting from benzaldehyde, benzyl alcohol, benzonitrile, and methyl benzoate.
[src:anise/agaricus-subrufescens] Used in traditional and alternative medicine for its supposed anti-cancer effects, *Agaricus* mushrooms have not been assessed by sufficient high-quality clinical research to define safety and biological properties upon consumption as a food, dietary supplement, or drug.
[src:anise/anise] The flavor and aroma of its seeds have similarities with some other spices and herbs, such as star anise, fennel, liquorice, and tarragon.
[src:anise/anise] It is widely cultivated and used to flavor food, candy, and alcoholic drinks, especially around the Mediterranean.
[src:anise/anise] The name "anise" is derived via Old French from the Latin words *anīsum* or *anēthum* from Greek ἄνηθον *ánēthon* referring to dill.
[src:anise/anise] An obsolete English word for anise is *anet*, also coming from *ănēthum*.
[src:anise/anise] Anise is an herbaceous annual plant growing to 60–90 centimetres (2–3 feet) or more.
[src:anise/anise] The leaves at the base of the plant are simple, 1–5 cm (3⁄8–2 inches) long and shallowly lobed, while leaves higher on the stems are feathery or lacy, pinnate, divided into numerous small leaflets.
[src:anise/anise] Both leaves and flowers are produced in large, loose clusters.
[src:anise/anise] The flowers are either white or yellow, approximately 3 millimetres (1⁄8 in) in diameter, produced in dense umbels.
[src:anise/anise] The fruit is a dry oblong and curved schizocarp, 4–6 mm (1⁄6–1⁄4 in) long, usually called "aniseed".
[src:anise/anise] Anise is a food plant for the larvae of some Lepidoptera species (butterflies and moths), including the lime-speck pug and wormwood pug.
[src:anise/anise] Anise was first cultivated in the Middle East, and was brought to Europe for its medicinal value.
[src:anise/anise] It has been cultivated in Egypt for approximately 4,000 years.
[src:anise/anise] Anise plants grow best in light, fertile, well-drained soil.
[src:anise/anise] The seeds should be planted as soon as the ground warms up in spring.
[src:anise/anise] Because the plants have a taproot, they do not transplant well after being established so they should either be started in their final location or be transplanted while the seedlings are still small.
[src:anise/anise] Western cuisines have long used anise to flavor dishes, drinks, and candies.
[src:anise/anise] The word is used for both the species of herb and its licorice-like flavor.
[src:anise/anise] The most powerful flavor component of the essential oil of anise, anethole, is found in both anise and an unrelated spice indigenous to South China called star anise (*Illicium verum*) widely used in South Asian, Southeast Asian and East Asian dishes.
[src:anise/anise] Star anise is considerably less expensive to produce and has gradually displaced *P. anisum* in Western markets.
[src:anise/anise] While formerly produced in larger quantities, by 1999 world production of the essential oil of anise was 8 tons, compared to 400 tons of star anise.
[src:anise/anise] As with all spices, the composition of anise varies considerably with origin and cultivation method.
[src:anise/anise] These are typical values for the main constituents.
[src:anise/anise] In particular, the anise seeds products should also contain more than 0.2 milliliter volatile oil per 100 grams of spice.
[src:anise/anise] Anise is sweet and aromatic, distinguished by its characteristic flavor.
[src:anise/anise] The culinary uses of anise are not limited only to sweets and confections, as it is a key ingredient in Mexican *atole de anís* and *champurrado*, which is similar to hot chocolate.
[src:anise/anise] In India and Pakistan, it is taken as a digestive after meals, used in brines in the Italian region of Apulia and as a flavoring agent in Italian sausage, pepperoni and other Italian processed meat products.
[src:anise/anise] The freshly chopped leaves are added to cheese spreads, dips or salads, while roots and stems impart a mild licorice flavor to soups and stews.
[src:anise/anise] Outside the Mediterranean region, it is found in Colombian *aguardiente* and Mexican *Xtabentún*.
[src:anise/anise] These liqueurs are clear, but on addition of water become cloudy, a phenomenon known as the ouzo effect or louche.
[src:anise/anise] Anise is used together with other herbs and spices in some root beers, such as Virgil's in the United States.
[src:anise/anise] According to Pliny the Elder, anise was used as a cure for sleeplessness, chewed with alexanders and a little honey in the morning to freshen the breath, and, when mixed with wine, as a remedy for asp bites (N.H.
[src:anise/anise] In 19th-century medicine, anise was prepared as **aqua anisi** ("Water of Anise") in doses of an ounce or more and as **spiritus anisi** ("Spirit of Anise") in doses of 5–20 minims.
[src:anise/anise] In Turkish folk medicine, its seeds have been used as an appetite stimulant, tranquilizer or diuretic.
[src:anise/anise] Anise essential oil can be obtained from the fruits by either steam distillation or extraction using supercritical carbon dioxide.
[src:anise/anise] The yield of essential oil is influenced by the growing conditions and extraction process, with supercritical extraction being more efficient.
[src:anise/anise] Regardless of the method of isolation the main component of the oil is anethole (80–90%), with minor components including 4-anisaldehyde, estragole and pseudoisoeugenyl-2-methylbutyrates amongst others.
[src:anise/anise] 2008 to be 2–6% extracted oil by weight of raw seed material, 74–94% being *trans*-anethole and the remaining fraction estragole (methylchavicol), anisaldehyde and γ-himachalene.) Anethole is responsible for anise's characteristic odor and flavor.
[src:anise/anise] Builders of steam locomotives in Britain incorporated capsules of aniseed oil into white metal plain bearings so the distinctive smell would give warning in case of overheating.
[src:anise/anise] Anise can be made into a liquid scent and is used for both drag hunting and fishing.
[src:anise/anise] It is put on fishing lures to attract fish.
